 high-quality research articles in order to examine one aspect of the political mechanism of modern China, from empire to the PRC: political initiatives to root out corruption. Proceeding chronologically, the eleven chapters explore modern political history through a particular focus on the anti-corruption campaigns of early modern and modern China. Our interdisciplinary analysis draws on methodologies from several distinct fields, including political science, civil law, and mass media. Such an analysis reveals the unique characteristics of China’s urbanization, which have transformed not only the country, but also the CCP – from a rural-based totalitarian party to a city-centered authoritarian party, and from a party of the people to a party of powerful interest groups by 2002–2016.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aAsian Studies. 4aAsian history. 4aChina. 4aGeopolitics. 4aInternational Relations. 4aInternational relations. 4aNorth America (USA and Canada). 4aPolitics and Government. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aChina-US relations, International Relations, geopolitics, global economy, post-Cold War diplomacy, security concerns, transnationalism, multiculturalism.1 aChambers, Travis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFang, Qiang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFang, Qiang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFuliang Shan, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHou, Xiaojia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Xiaobing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Xiaobing, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLi, Xiaoxiao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca